    {
      "id": "ac128ee3556fcc70ed32e95723558c5ba2fc9402",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-04 06:33:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nMy preference would be to have little helper functions to do the cleanup, line \"cleanup_2()v\" that do the actual cleanup and clear the trap condition, and this is explicitly called at the end of a function, instead of only implicitly being called when the function exits normally. I think that makes the tests easier to follow for people who are not familiar with bash.\n\nRegardless of whether you like that suggestion or not, it would be good to do the cleanup consistently for all the tests - either having a function do the cleanup, or doing it implicitly with the registered trap. In test_27* it registers the trap but then clears it and does the cleanup manually. \n\nIn test_110() it would be good to clean up the code to generate the pathname rather than having ~280-character long lines.\n\nThere are a number if other minor style issues in the nearby lines (extraneous linefeed escape '\\' at the end of a line after && or ||, too long lines, removal of \"=====\" in test description, use of $tdir and $tfile instead of explicit test nimbers, and tab indentations that could be done in these tests. Not critical, but nice to do while this code is being updated.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
